Orchestrates a single cage run's three-phase lifecycle (prepare → run → teardown), delegating each phase to a private submodule (`prepare`, `run`, `teardown`, plus `env` for `bwrap` config bind/env resolution used by `run`). This file itself holds only shared types and the top-level driver — no phase logic.

`Resolved` is the fully-resolved input struct built by host binaries from parsed CLI args plus path resolution of the `ctx-verify`/`ctx-context`/`ctx-scan` binaries bound into the cage; `target_root` must be canonicalized before use (see below). `RunOutcome` carries the caged process's `exit_code` plus an optional capped `diagnostic` string — the diagnostic is best-effort reporting only and never overrides `exit_code` (mirrors ADR-027's philosophy, also followed by `teardown_run`).

`execute(r: &Resolved) -> Result<RunOutcome, CageError>` is the sole entry point: canonicalizes `target_root`, calls `prepare::prepare_run`, then `run::run_until_exit`, then unconditionally calls `teardown::teardown_run` regardless of whether `run` succeeded — a crashed bwrap or proxy thread never strands the run dir. Teardown errors are swallowed.

`canonicalize_target` resolves `target_root` to an absolute canonical path before the lifecycle proceeds. This is load-bearing: per ADR-046, `bwrap` binds `target_root` at the identical path inside the cage alongside other always-absolute binds (`/cage/bin`, `/opt/cage/rules.md`, `/run/ctx`). A relative `target_root` (e.g. `.` from `ctx-run .`) mixes relative and absolute destinations in one `bwrap` invocation, causing `bwrap` to create the mount points as real directories on the host disk instead of inside the sandbox — silent host filesystem pollution, not a crash.